voters turn out to be strongly
in favor of

23:21.934 --> 23:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
remaining. And we will explore
that side of
the debate, to remain, in our
next piece.

23:28.274 --> 23:35.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Until then, reporting from
Oxford, England,
this is economics correspondent
Paul Solman.

23:35.781 --> 23:48.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to a major
change being
made by the U.S. Navy that will
affect servicemen

23:48.360 --> 23:51.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suffering from one of the unseen
wounds of
war.

23:51.730 --> 23:53.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has that.

23:53.532 --> 23:57.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The wars in Iraq and
Afghanistan
have killed thousands of
American servicemen

23:57.469 --> 24:03.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and maimed and injured tens of
thousands more,
but some wounds are not as
easily seen or

24:03.175 --> 24:04.977 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
identified.

24:05.010 --> 24:10.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Post-traumatic stress disorder,
or PTSD afflicts
as much as one-fifth of Iraq and
Afghanistan

24:10.916 --> 24:16.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
veterans in any given year.
Compounding the
affliction, personnel who were
kicked out

24:16.355 --> 24:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the military because of
erratic behavior
caused by PTSD, by traumatic
brain injury,

24:23.329 --> 24:28.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called TBI, or by other mental
health conditions
often lose their benefits,
including access

24:28.967 --> 24:30.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to veterans health care.

24:30.836 --> 24:36.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that will now change for at
least one
of the services, navy personnel,
sailors and

24:36.175 --> 24:40.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Marines, under a new policy
enacted by Navy
Secretary Ray Mabus.

24:40.646 --> 24:42.247 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Secretary Mabus joins us now.

24:42.281 --> 24:43.449 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you for joining us.

24:43.482 --> 24:44.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAY MABUS, Secretary of the U.S.
Navy: Glad
to be here.

24:44.983 --> 24:48.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Tell us what this new
policy is
and why you made this change.

24:48.954 --> 24:54.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAY MABUS: The policy that we
had been operating
under was, if somebody committed
misconduct,

24:54.760 --> 24:59.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the erratic behavior you were
talking about,
that took preference over
everything else

24:59.365 --> 25:01.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in terms of a discharge.

25:01.166 --> 25:06.638 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so people would get
discharged with bad
paper, with discharges that
didn't give them

25:06.672 --> 25:12.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
any benefits when they left.
What we have
done with policy that I have
just signed was

25:12.911 --> 25:17.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to say, if you're being
administratively discharged
for some misconduct, we're going
to take a

25:17.950 --> 25:23.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
look to see if you have got a
diagnosable
condition, to see if you have
got PTSD, to

25:23.222 --> 25:29.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see if you have got traumatic
brain injury,
and then that will factor in, so
that you

25:29.328 --> 25:34.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
may still be discharged, but you
will be discharged
with benefits, with help that
we're going

25:35.000 --> 25:41.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to recognize the reason for this
erratic behavior
and give you help after you
leave the military.

25:41.206 --> 25:48.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's not just for combat
injuries, combat
wounds. It's also for things
like sexual assault

25:48.514 --> 25:51.083 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that is often followed by PTSD.

25:51.116 --> 25:54.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And just to be clear,
you say that
this conduct took precedence.

25:54.753 --> 25:59.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In other words, it didn't matter
that the
misconduct may have had an
underlying cause.

25:59.691 --> 26:01.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RAY MABUS: Right.

26:01.460 --> 26:07.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only thing that was looked
at was the
misconduct. And the discharge
was based on

26:07.666 --> 26:16.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that misconduct without why it
was caused,
without PTSD evaluation, without
TBI evaluation.

26:17.009 --> 26:24.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the awful thing was, when
people left
under this circumstance, they
got no benefits.

26:24.850 --> 26:30.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they couldn't get into
veterans health
care. They couldn't get the
assistance they

26:30.389 --> 26:37.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
needed to deal with PTSD or to
deal with traumatic
brain injury. It was a pure
policy issue.

26:37.196 --> 26:42.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is not just for people
being discharged
now, not just for active-duty
people. If you're

26:42.367 --> 26:47.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a veteran, and you were
discharged and got
bad paper, and so you're not
getting any benefits,

26:47.806 --> 26:54.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and you believe that it was
caused by in some
way or another PTSD or traumatic
brain injury,

26:54.646 --> 26:56.982 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
come back. We will take another
look at it.

26:57.015 --> 27:04.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will take another run at the
determination
of the discharge. If it is found
by that,

27:04.957 --> 27:10.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you will be able to get your
benefits, even
if you have been discharged for
a while.

27:10.729 --> 27:13.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Any idea how many men
and women
that could affect?

27:13.765 --> 27:19.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAY MABUS: The estimates we have
got on traumatic
brain injury are 46,000 sailors,
49,000 Marines.

27:19.071 --> 27:25.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a lot of people. It's
hard to know,
in terms of why people were
discharged, why

27:25.978 --> 27:28.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- what kind of discharges they
got.

27:28.280 --> 27:33.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This sort of thing, it's hard to
know how
many are going to fit in under
that, but it's

27:33.385 --> 27:35.220 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
clearly not just a few people.

27:35.254 --> 27:38.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Do you think enough
is being done
for sailors and Marines to
recognize, on the

27:39.024 --> 27:45.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commanders' part, to recognize
when behavior
may be because of PTSD or
traumatic brain

27:45.130 --> 27:46.231 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
injury?

27:46.265 --> 27:48.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAY MABUS: I think we're making
progress on
that.

27:48.200 --> 27:52.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other part of this policy is
that, if
you're going to be discharged
and there's

27:52.938 --> 28:00.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a possibility you will be
discharged without
benefits, that discharge
decision was moved

28:00.512 --> 28:05.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way up in the chain of command.
It has got
to be done by an admiral or a
general, a flag

28:05.551 --> 28:11.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officer, instead of where it
used to be, which
was a unit commander, which
would be lieutenant

28:11.857 --> 28:13.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
colonel, colonel, somewhere
around in there.

28:13.659 --> 28:18.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Secretary, do you
think the
other services will follow your
lead on this?

28:18.630 --> 28:20.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAY MABUS: Well, I certainly
hope so.

28:20.465 --> 28:27.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have had some talks with
the other
services on how we implemented
this and what

28:27.205 --> 28:31.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the new policy is. And so this
is the right
thing to do.

28:31.143 --> 28:35.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Let me ask you one
more question
about an issue facing the modern
military.

28:35.847 --> 28:40.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Pentagon just recently had
their LGBT
pride event.

28:40.552 --> 28:45.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secretary Carter said last year
that he would
-- was looking to change the
policy to allow

28:45.991 --> 28:52.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
